						<summary>

						<p>West wall of the store room in the Tiruttaḷīśvara temple.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">c. 13th Centuary A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>It records an undertaking given by the <hi rend="italic">mūlaparushai-mahāsabhai</hi> to one Avanimuḻuduḍaiyār, wife of Dēvar Kaṇḍaṉ who endowed the amount received from Sundaṉammaiyāḻvi as <hi rend="italic">mūlaparushai-kaṇkāṇi dravyam</hi> for the supply of four water pots for the sacred bath during the midday <hi rend="italic">sandhi</hi> to be conducted to god Tiruttaḷiyāṇḍa-nāyaṉār of Tirupputtūr in Kēraḷaśiṅga-vaḷanāḍu. The <hi rend="italic">Śivabrāhmaṇas</hi> of the temple undertook to carry out the daily supply of water-pots from out of the gift amount received.</p>						

						</summary>
